[
    {
        "content": "<p>Type variables in many ML derived languages use a single letter from an alphabetic sequence and don't convey any meaning about them to the user.  Many beginners struggle with this, and even experienced programmers find them less understandable in long type signatures.</p>\n<p>i propose that in the Roc standard library, official packages and platforms, and documentation we use and promote the use of semantically meaningful type variable names</p>\n<p>So <code>List(item)</code> over <code>List(a)</code><br>\nAnd <code>Map(key, value)</code> over <code>Map(a, b)</code> or even <code>Map(k, v)</code></p>\n<p>Etc</p>",
        "id": 527008506,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552224
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>regarding meaningful type var names - for years I did this in Elm and I honestly have mixed feelings about it in retrospect</p>",
        "id": 527009024,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552351
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>in Elm I would write things this all the time:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">cancelButton</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Html</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">msg</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">cancelButton</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">button</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">text</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"Ok\"</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"p\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 527009037,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552355
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>instead of this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">cancelButton</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Html</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">cancelButton</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">button</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">text</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"Ok\"</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"p\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 527009047,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552361
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I really like the idea of meaningful names in std.</p>\n<p>How do you think this would look like?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>map2 :\n    Result a err,\n    Result b err,\n    (a, b -&gt; c)\n    -&gt; Result c err\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 527009515,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751552467
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>one downside I encountered in practice: when talking about this out loud (e.g. in meetups) I'd always be saying \"HTML msg with a little M\" because if I just said \"HTML msg\" they wouldn't know what I was talking about. \"HTML a\" doesn't have that problem. (Neither does \"HTML star\" which was one of my motivations for trying out <code>*</code>.)</p>",
        "id": 527009546,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552478
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would say <code>HTML for some message</code></p>",
        "id": 527009994,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552610
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>another consideration:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">elem_a</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">elem_a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">elem_b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">elem_b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">ok_a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">ok_a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">ok_b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">ok_b</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">elem1</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">elem1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">elem2</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">elem2</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">ok1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">ok1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">ok2</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">ok2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 527010036,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552621
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I use this example because here there's tension between consistent naming for container elements and consistent naming across <code>map</code>s</p>",
        "id": 527010276,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552687
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the last example is consistently using <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> across <code>map</code> functions</p>",
        "id": 527010348,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552707
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the first two are also using a consistent convention (<code>_a</code>/<code>_b</code> suffix or <code>1</code>/<code>2</code> suffix) but they're a lot longer to read</p>",
        "id": 527010463,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552733
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I feel like</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">src</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">src</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">dest</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">dest</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"nf\">.</span><span class=\"nv\">map</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">src</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">),</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">src</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">dest</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">dest</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>is more logical than using numbers or letters</p>",
        "id": 527010528,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552751
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah, or <code>before</code>/<code>after</code></p>",
        "id": 527010569,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552760
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a class=\"message-link\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/304641-ideas/topic/Unbound.20type.20variable.20naming.20conventions/near/527009515\">#ideas &gt; Unbound type variable naming conventions @ 💬</a></p>",
        "id": 527010599,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751552768
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>src</code>/<code>dest</code> is cool, I'd never thought about those!</p>",
        "id": 527010628,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552773
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, just something to tell the reader of the type what we are doing with those types</p>",
        "id": 527010710,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552797
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Elm does this, but not for the core data structures</p>",
        "id": 527010861,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552829
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">map_both</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">src1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">src2</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">src1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">src2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">dest</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">dest</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 527010884,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552834
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>that looks pretty nice to me</p>",
        "id": 527010944,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552852
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah me too</p>",
        "id": 527010972,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552860
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>better than</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">map_both</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">),</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">c</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">c</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">err</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 527011014,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751552874
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yep</p>",
        "id": 527011072,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552888
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think thinking about the type vars should be put under the same scrutiny as every other part of a type or functions api</p>",
        "id": 527011183,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552917
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Like what does this function do?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">Task</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">x</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Task</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">y</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Id</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>if you didn't write the book on Elm? <span aria-label=\"wink\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f609\" role=\"img\" title=\"wink\">:wink:</span></p>",
        "id": 527011465,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751552991
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think in each case it depends on the function itself. Like, <code>map_both</code> and <code>map</code> give the context for other names</p>",
        "id": 527011648,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751553035
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yep, which means you can communicate via types much more easily, and also DESIGN with types with more clarity</p>",
        "id": 527011985,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751553108
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Task(error, value) := [Task(error, value)]</p>\n<p>is easy to understand and i don't even have to read the docs to get the basic idea</p>",
        "id": 527012371,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751553210
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>as opposed to Task(x, a) as Elm does today</p>",
        "id": 527012552,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751553257
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"781658\">Anthony Bullard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/304641-ideas/topic/Unbound.20type.20variable.20naming.20conventions/near/527011465\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Like what does this function do?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kt\">Task</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Task</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Id</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>if you didn't write the book on Elm? <span aria-label=\"wink\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f609\" role=\"img\" title=\"wink\">:wink:</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>amusingly, in Elm, I can tell just from the type that it returns <code>Task.fail someHardcodedId</code> and anything else it does before that is just heating up the CPU at best or crashing/infinite looping at worst <span aria-label=\"laughing\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f606\" role=\"img\" title=\"laughing\">:laughing:</span></p>",
        "id": 527025089,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751556637
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but yes, in general I agree - thinking harder about type variable names is good!</p>",
        "id": 527025167,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751556665
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what would be a good one for <code>Num</code>?</p>",
        "id": 527027456,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751557294
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>like what would be better than <code>a</code> here?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">answer</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Num</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nv\">a</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">answer</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">42</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 527027509,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751557312
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>elem</code> is an obvious choice for <code>List</code>, but I'm not sure what it would be for <code>Num</code></p>",
        "id": 527027571,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751557331
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>for me, it depends on context. is <code>Num(a)</code> a thing on it's own?</p>",
        "id": 527027888,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751557434
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but <code>value</code> seems to be valid by default.<br>\nupd. probably weird<br>\n<code>Num.add : Num(value), Num(value) -&gt; Num(value)</code></p>",
        "id": 527028041,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751557488
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but I think for collections it describes what's being contained, e.g.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Ruby\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"no\">List</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">elem</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"no\">Dict</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">key</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">val</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"no\">Result</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">ok</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">err</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"no\">Num</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">value</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>the last one feels out of place to me, because really the type variable is describing the precision of the number - e.g. is it an integer or frac, how many bits, float vs decimal, etc.</p>",
        "id": 527032145,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751558761
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>Num(precision)</code> is too long though, and <code>Num(prec)</code> doesn't feel very self-descriptive</p>",
        "id": 527032236,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751558789
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>could be like <code>Num(size)</code> I guess?</p>",
        "id": 527032269,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751558802
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ah, indeed. I forgot <code>Num</code> is a container around other types. I was thinking about smth like <code>I8(value)</code>. and that's another example of how meaningful var names can help. <code>size</code> helps me to remember the fact that I'm not manipulating a number, but a number of a certain size</p>",
        "id": 527033085,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751559073
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>Num(range)</code> is another contender</p>",
        "id": 527033352,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751559154
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>since it's like \"a number of a certain range\" although that gets a little weird when you get into the fact that floating-point numbers lose precision outside certain ranges</p>",
        "id": 527033418,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751559175
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like <code>size</code> a bit better, not sure why though</p>",
        "id": 527033538,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751559213
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>because <code>usize</code> :)</p>",
        "id": 527033591,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751559228
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think maybe because <code>range</code> kind of suggests to me that you can control the exact range, like \"oh I want this number to be between exactly 42 to 76\"</p>",
        "id": 527033694,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1751559265
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, that's what I thought as well</p>",
        "id": 527034562,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751559614
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I just checked wikipedia, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_(computer_science)?wprov=sfti1\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_(computer_science)?wprov=sfti1#</a></p>\n<p><code>size</code> is everywhere there. Very natural term</p>",
        "id": 527034802,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751559709
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>size or precision i would think</p>",
        "id": 527036742,
        "sender_full_name": "Anthony Bullard",
        "timestamp": 1751560447
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281383\">Richard Feldman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/304641-ideas/topic/Unbound.20type.20variable.20naming.20conventions/near/527010569\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>yeah, or <code>before</code>/<code>after</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I've never thought about it, but now I can't unsee it. Why are 'before' and 'after' alphabetically opposite to 'a' and 'b'??</p>\n<p>But yeah for some on-topic feedback. I prefer slightly descriptive type variable names as well. I feel like one of the reasons they aren't in haskell is because it's harder to do for the more abstract higher-kinded type variables. Also math</p>",
        "id": 527106689,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1751604870
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like descriptive type variables as well, my current preference goes to the numbered style <code>ok1</code>. We don't use numbers elsewhere so it's an easy to way to spot a type variable.</p>",
        "id": 527139405,
        "sender_full_name": "Anton",
        "timestamp": 1751620326
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Perhaps something with <code>in</code> and <code>out</code> could work too. <code>src</code> and <code>dest</code> make me think of other things.</p>",
        "id": 527142639,
        "sender_full_name": "Anton",
        "timestamp": 1751621423
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>from/to also</p>",
        "id": 527142927,
        "sender_full_name": "Kiryl Dziamura",
        "timestamp": 1751621521
    }
]